The Lebanese crisis
Beirut — — looking back, it usually seems that there were warning signs before a financial crisis occurred; however, they rarely clearly indicate the course of history.
The Lebanese situation is also like that, a predictable crisis has plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the Lebanese situation is already compared with the Lebanese crisis, it is likely that the historical translation of '黎巴嫩' in the source sentence should be 'Lebanese' instead of 'Lebanon', in order to maintain consistency with the preceding translation style.
At some point, external capital inflow had to come to a stop. This point arrived at the end of 2019, which was followed by a series of negative shocks.
This abrupt halt in capital gave the country a severe triple crisis.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
The Lebanese country's current-account deficit reached as high as 25% of its GDP, with its export base being too small to even cover the necessary costs of imported goods.
The second issue is the budget.
The Lebanese country's public debt now totals over 150% of its GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the heavy pressure of economic recession, with the budget deficit already large, at 10% of GDP in 2019, and still rapidly expanding.
The Lebanese country is also experiencing a banking crisis.
The main banks, as the primary recipients of foreign capital inflow, have made substantial investments in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their portfolios), and now are essentially insolvent.
These crises together will push the Lebanese economy into the abyss.
Companies that are eager to borrow and import have already begun laying off employees or shutting down completely.
Economic recession may lead to a major depression in Lebanon.
The main capital source supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but expatriates, who are drawn to invest due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate pegged to the US dollar.
It's hardly surprising that signs of the "Dutch disease" can be seen everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has lowered the national savings rate to an implausible level of 3% of GDP.
The level of inequality is very high and continues to rise.
Between 2000 and 2015, the effective exchange rate appreciated by around 50%, significantly weakening the tradable sector.
Due to a lack of exportable goods and services, Lebanon has been losing educated young people.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflow has allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their position through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have extracted wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated patronage regime.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, while the broader macroeconomic challenges have not been addressed at all.
The financial crisis has sparked a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement has taken to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, the government's response to Lebanon's economic crisis has been overwhelmingly skewed towards the elite, suggesting that this crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle classes, thereby further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the government refused to impose capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank, including politicians in power, to decide how to withdraw cash in quantity.
In practice, this allows the elite to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
In addition, the central bank has lowered deposit rates, but not yet lowered public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Although international reserves have been declining steadily, Lebanon has continued to service its foreign debt owed mainly to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may start selling off state assets to elite-affiliated entities at fire-sale prices.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, allowing the elite to obtain dollars at a low rate, while ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly declining free-market exchange rate. The free-market exchange rate is currently trading at a 40% discount.
When the government starts printing the lira to pay public salaries, depreciation will accelerate.
In practice, the central bank has started paying interest on dollar deposits in lira (dollar deposits account for over 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to erode public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction through "liraization" is shifted to depositors, the banks' capital is largely spared.
If this scenario becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle classes would significantly decline due to a reduction in actual wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The educated young people's emigration process will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the emigrant community - which this system relies on - will be damaged.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will govern a population of the poor, who can be increasingly controlled by an ever-cheaper shelter.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
In contrast, the establishment of a new republic driven by revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to reform Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and achievements, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They aspire to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more sustainable environmentally, position the country as a cultural hub, and foster greater synergy with the expatriate community.
To achieve these objectives, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which would be secured by bank equity and would compel a 1% withdrawal of depositors who hold over 50% of total deposits.
They support a moderate devaluation of the currency and a comprehensive improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They aim to pursue a deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corruption and increasing expenditures on social projects and infrastructure.
In the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current infighting over the composition of the next Lebanese cabinet is a part of the larger struggle in the country's quest for a new political solution.
The financial crisis poses a mortal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future hangs in the balance.
